problem:
As shown in the figure, a ping-pong ball with mass $m$ with initial horizontal velocity $v$ and angular velocity $\omega$ comes into contact with the ground. Friction is not negligible, so both the velocity and angular velocity of the ping-pong ball changes. What is the critical velocity $v_c$ such that the ping-pong will stop and remain stopped? Treat the ping-pong ball as a hollow sphere.
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.2]{fma1}
    \end{center}
    \begin{enumerate}[label = (\Alph*)]
\item $v=\frac23R\omega$
\item $v=\frac25R\omega$
\item $v=R\omega$
\item $v=\frac35R\omega$
\item $v=\frac53R\omega$
\end{enumerate}

A thin rod has a nonuniform density. It is mounted on an axle passing perpendicular to it, through its center of mass, as shown, and is then rotated about the axle.
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.2]{fma2}
    \end{center}
    The axle divides the rod into two parts, one on each side of it. Which of the following must be true, no matter how the mass in the rod is distributed?
    \begin{enumerate}[label = (\Alph*)]
\item The two parts have the same mass.
\item The magnitudes of the momenta of the two parts are equal.
\item The magnitudes of the angular momenta of the two parts, about the center of mass, are equal.
\item The kinetic energies of the two parts are equal.
\item At least two of the above are true.
\end{enumerate}

A hollow sphere of mass $m$ and radius $r$ is filled entirely with water of a total mass $M$. The sphere is placed on an inclined plane at a height $h$ and begins rolling down without slipping. However, assume that there is no friction between the water and the inside of the sphere so that the movement of the water is purely translational.
    \begin{anum}
        \item Find the minimum coefficient of friction $\mu$ needed between the plane and the sphere in order for the sphere to roll without slipping. 
        \item Find the translational velocity of the sphere $v$ at the bottom of the incline.
    \end{anum}

solution:
\begin{anum}
        \item Let the friction force be $f$. By force analysis parallel to the plane, $$(m+M)g\sin\theta-f=(m+M)a$$And by torque analysis relative to the COM, (since the water does not rotate, we only consider the sphere) $$fr=\frac23mr^2\alpha\Rightarrow f=\frac23ma$$Solving the system of equations for $f$ yields $$f=\frac{2m(m+M)g\sin\theta}{5m+3M}$$The minimum coefficient of friction is achieved when $f=N\mu=(m+M)g\cos\theta\mu$, so $$\mu=\boxed{\frac{2m}{5m+3M}\tan\theta}$$
        \item The total kinetic energy at the bottom of the ramp is given by energy of the sphere plus the energy of the water. The total energy of the sphere is given by $$K_s=\frac12mv^2+\frac12\frac23mr^2\omega^2=\frac56mv^2$$and since the energy of the water is purely translational, the total energy is thus $$K=\frac56mv^2+\frac12Mv^2$$Equating this to the decrease in potential energy $(m+M)gh$ yields $$v=\boxed{\sqrt{\frac{6(m+M)gh}{5m+3M}}}$$
    \end{anum}

By conservation of angular momentum about the contact point, $$v_x-\frac25R\omega=v_x'-\frac25R\omega'\Rightarrow v_x-v_x'=\frac25(R\omega-R\omega')$$By conservation of energy, $$\frac12mv_x^2+\frac12\frac25mR^2\omega^2=\frac12m{v_x'}^2+\frac12\frac25mR^2{\omega'}^2\Rightarrow v_x^2-{v_x'}^2=\frac25(R^2{\omega'}^2-R^2\omega^2)$$Dividing the energy equation by angular momentum, $$v_x+v_x'=-(R\omega'+R\omega)$$And solving this equation with conjunction with the angular momentum equation yields \begin{gather*}
    \boxed{v_x'=\frac17(3v_x-4R\omega)}\\
    \boxed{R\omega'=-\frac17(10v_x+3R\omega)}
\end{gather*}

problem:
A (possibly non-uniform) stick of mass $m$ and length $l$ lies on frictionless ice. Its midpoint (which is also its COM) touches a thin pole sticking out of the ice. One end of the stick is struck with a quick blow perpendicular to the stick so that the COM moves away from the pole. What is the minimum value of the stick’s moment of inertia that allows the stick not to hit the pole?
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.2]{morin1}
    \end{center}

solution:
If $P$ is the impulse applied, let $v=P/m$ be the velocity of the COM and $\omega=P(l/2)/I$ be the rotational velocity. For the rod to not hit the pole, the COM has to move a distance $l/2$ before the pole rotates $90^\circ$, or $\pi/4$ radians. Thus, in the critical case we require \begin{align*}
        \frac{l}{2v}=\frac{\pi}{4\omega}\Rightarrow I=\boxed{\frac{1}{\pi}ml^2}
    \end{align*}

