A bead is placed on a horizontal rail, along which it can slide frictionlessly. It is attached to the end of a rigid, massless rod of length $R$. A ball is attached at the other end. Both the bead and the ball have mass $M$. The system is initially stationary, with the ball directly above the bead. The ball is then given an infinitesimal push, parallel to the rail.
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.2]{usapho1}
    \end{center}
    Assume that the rod and ball are designed in such a way (not shown explicitly in the diagram) so that they can pass through the rail without hitting it. In other words, the rail only constrains the motion of the bead. 
    \begin{anum}
        \item Derive an expression for the force in the rod when the ball is directly below the bead as shown. 
        \begin{center}
            \includegraphics[scale=0.15]{usapho2}
        \end{center}
        \item Let $\theta$ be the angle the rod makes with the vertical, so that the rod begins at $\theta = 0$. Find the angular velocity $\omega$ as a function of $\theta$.
    \end{anum}

solution:
\begin{anum}
    \item This part was sourced from USAPhO 2019, problem B3, part b. For a tricker version of this problem, give a shot at part a \href{https://www.aapt.org/physicsteam/upload/2019_USAPhO.pdf}{here}. By conservation of energy, the total kinetic energy of the system is $2MgR$ at the position shown. Notice that there is no horizontal force on the system, so the total momentum in the $x$ direction must be conserved. As a result, at this particular moment the top mass is moving to the right at some $v$ and the bottom mass is moving to the left at some $v$. Applying conservation of energy, $$2\frac12Mv^2=2MgR\Rightarrow v=\sqrt{2gR}$$The motion of each mass in this frame is quite complicated, so it's helpful to analyze the situation in the rest frame of the top mass. Notice that the top mass is not accelerating at this moment, since the only possible acceleration it could have would be in the horizontal plane (because of the normal force provided by the rail), and no horizontal forces act on this mass at the moment described (this condition is not true for part a of the USAPhO problem). As a result, we can switch into this instantaneous velocity frame without introducing fictitious forces. In this frame, the bottom mass moves in a circle of radius $R$ at speed $2v$, so the tension in the rod is easily found by balancing forces: $$T-Mg=M\frac{(2v)^2}{R}=8Mg\Rightarrow T=\boxed{9Mg}$$
    \item The height of the ball is $R \cos\theta$, so the released gravitational potential energy is $MgR(1-\cos\theta)$. The kinetic energy may be decomposed into rotation about the center of mass and translation of the center of mass; this translation is purely vertical by conservation of momentum. The vertical speed of the center of mass is $(R/2)\omega \sin \theta$, so the kinetic energy is$$\frac12I_0\omega^2+\frac12(2M)v^2=\frac14MR^2\omega^2(1+\sin^2\theta)$$Equating these two equations and simplifying gives $$\omega=\boxed{\sqrt{\frac{4g}{R}\frac{1-\cos\theta}{1+\sin^2\theta}}}$$
\end{anum}

